An official gauge of activity in China’s manufacturing industry fell slightly in October, while consumer spending helped to lift services output, suggesting the economic recovery remains on track. “The data suggest there is no urgency for the government to add fresh stimulus by year-end, though we expect an easing bias to be maintained. The only tarnish on an otherwise solid set of data was a drop in the PMI for small companies, which slipped back into contractionary territory.” -- Chang Shu, chief Asia economist Click here to read the full report. — With assistance by John Liu, Lin Zhu, and April Ma